give.n <- function(x){
  return(c(y = mean(x)*1.13, label = length(x))) 
}

semPaths(fit.3factors.second, "std", weighted = FALSE, nCharNodes = 7, shapeMan = "rectangle",

Three-factors model alternative with second order:

semPaths(fit.3factors.alt.second, "std", weighted = FALSE, nCharNodes = 7, shapeMan = "rectangle",
         sizeMan = 8,  intercepts = FALSE, edge.label.cex = 1, curvePivot = TRUE)

In both models, there is an issue with the expert.based latent variable, which has negative variance. Further investigation is needed to determine the cause of this problem. Theoretically, it would make sense to add an second order as we expect the three dimensions to be related. THat is, we see these dimensions as part of a bigger latent variable (policy credibility).
